<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Dudleya greenei  </i>(CRPR 4.2) is a characteristic species of the alliance and is endemic to the northern Channel Islands.  <i>Astragalus miguelensis </i>(CRPR 4.3) is often present.  All of the following species tracked by the CNPS Rare Plant Inventory (2015) occur in one out of four stands sampled for this alliance on San Miguel Island, <i>Lotus (=Acmispon) dendroideus </i>var. <i>veatchii </i>(CRPR 4.3), <i>Eriogonum grande  </i>var. <i>rubescens  </i>(CRPR 1B.2), <i>Erysimum insulare </i>(CRPR 1B.3), and <i>Malacothrix incana </i>(CRPR 4.3).<br/>
<br/>
This alliance appears to also occur on Santa Cruz Island cliff faces within a matrix of coastal bluff scrub that is exhibiting signs of recovery and expansion after the removal of sheep (Rodriguez et al. 2017). Additionally, other rare <i>Dudleya </i>species appear to occur in small patches on other northern and southern Channel Islands, on volcanic fields at San Quintin in Baja California, Mexico (Vanderplank 2011), and also on islands off the coast of Baja, including Cedros, Guadalupe, San Martin, and Todos Santos islands (Ratay et al. 2014). For example, <i>Dudleya nesiotica </i>densely covers several acres of gently sloping marine terraces with rocky clay soils at Fraser Point on Santa Cruz Island, and various subspecies of <i>Dudleya virens </i> occur along coastal bluffs of Santa Catalina Island and San Clemente Island (Junak et al. 2007). The largest number of endemics on the Channel Islands is within this genus <i>Dudleya</i>, and we need more sampling and analysis to determine their stand relationships with this and other similar alliances. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
