    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bc, Bh). This alliance is found on the northeastern portion of San Miguel Island. It is likely on other Channel Islands in California, and on Cedros and Guadalupe Islands in Mexico (Rodriguez et al. 2017).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Mesembryanthemum crystallinum </i>and other ice plant taxa threaten the Channel Island stands.  State and federal wildlife agents and the general public have identified a surge in <i>Dudleya </i>spp. Poaching along California coastlines. For example, along the North Coast poachers were caught stealing thousands of plants, shipping them internationally, and selling them in 2019 to 2020. Investigators estimated that poachers stole several hundreds of thousands of <i>Dudleya </i> plants.  A law  passed in 2021 makes it illegal to remove them from state and private lands without a permit or landowner permission and establishes penalties for those convicted of doing so (see Section 2024 of the Fish and Game Code). For a summary of <i>Dudleya </i>protections, also see: https://www.cnps.org/conservation/dudleya-protection. </div>
</div>

    

    

